<script>
let incomeList = [];

function addIncome() {
  const amount = document.getElementById('amount').value;
  const incomeType = document.getElementById('income-type').value;
  const notes = document.getElementById('notes').value;

  const incomeEntry = {
    amount: amount,
    type: incomeType,
    notes: notes
  };

  incomeList.push(incomeEntry);
  console.log(incomeList); // For debugging purposes, you can see the list in the console
  alert('Income added successfully!');
}
</script>

</body>
</html>
```

### Explanation:
- **JavaScript Function**: The `addIncome()` function captures the values from the input fields and stores them in an object. This object is then added to the `incomeList` array.
- **Button Click Event**: The `onclick` attribute of the "Add Income" button is set to call the `addIncome()` function when clicked.
- **Console Log**: The `console.log(incomeList);` statement is used to print the current list of incomes to the console for debugging purposes. You can remove it in production.

This setup will allow you to collect income data and store it in a list within the browser's memory."}],"context":{"currentFile":{"path":"income.html","fsPath":"/Users/Sakshi/PycharmProjects/fintrack/income.html","sources":["opened_tab"],"content":"<!DOCTYPE html>
