1. **HTML Structure**: Ensure your dropdown menu is correctly structured within your HTML. It seems you already have a basic structure in place.

2. **CSS for Dropdown**: You have a CSS class `.dropdown` that is initially set to `display: none;`. This is correct as it hides the dropdown by default.

3. **JavaScript for Interaction**: You need to add JavaScript to toggle the dropdown's visibility when a user interacts with it.

Here's how you can implement the JavaScript for your dropdown:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
<meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1">
<style>
body, html {
  height: 100%;
  margin: 0;
}

.input {
  border: none;
  border-bottom: 2px solid #03c6fc;
  padding: 10px;
  width: 70%;
  box-sizing: border-box;
  background-color: #030126;
  outline: none;
  color: white;
  font-family: "Times New Roman", Times, serif;
  font-size: 18px;
  margin: 0 auto;
  display: block;
}

.bg {
  background-image: url("img/bg.png");
  height: 100%;
  background-position: center;
  background-repeat: no-repeat;
  background-size: cover;
}

.rounded-corners{
  border-radius: 25px;
  border: 2px solid #030126;
  padding: 20px;
  width: 500px;
  height: 550px;
  background-color: #030126;
}

.text{
    color:white;
    font-family: "Times New Roman", Times, serif;
}

.button {
  background-color: #03c6fc;
  border: none;
  color: white;
  padding: 10px 20px;
  text-align: center;
  text-decoration: none;
  display: block;
  font-size: 18px;
  margin: 20px auto;
  cursor: pointer;
  border-radius: 5px;
  width: 70%;
  box-sizing: border-box;
}

.dropdown {
  display: none;
  position: absolute;
  background-color: #03c6fc;
  min-width: 160px;
  box-shadow: 0px 8px 16px 0px rgba(0,0,0,0.2);
  z-index: 1;
  border-radius: 4px;
}

.dropdown a {
  color: white;
  padding: 12px 16px;
  text-decoration: none;
  display: block;
  background-color: #03c6fc;
  border-radius: 4px;
}

.dropdown a:hover {background-color: #027ddb;}
</style>
</head>
<body class="bg">
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<center>
<div class="rounded-corners">
<h1 class="text">INCOME</h1>
    <input type="text" class="input" placeholder="Enter your income here"><br><br>
    <div id="addDropdown" class="dropdown">
      <a id="salary">Salary</a>
      <a id="business">Business</a>
    </div>
    <button onclick="toggleDropdown()" class="button">Add Income</button>
</div>
</center>
</body>
<script>
function toggleDropdown() {
  var dropdown = document.getElementById("addDropdown");
  dropdown.style.display = dropdown.style.display === "block" ? "none" : "block";
}

window.onclick = function(event) {
  if (!event.target.matches('.button')) {
    var dropdowns = document.getElementsByClassName("dropdown");
    for (var i = 0; i < dropdowns.length; i++) {
      var openDropdown = dropdowns[i];
      if (openDropdown.style.display === "block") {
        openDropdown.style.display = "none";
      }
    }
  }
}
</script>
</html>
```

### Explanation:
- **toggleDropdown Function**: This function toggles the display of the dropdown menu between `block` and `none` when the button is clicked.
- **Window Click Event**: This event listener closes the dropdown if the user clicks outside of it, ensuring the dropdown only stays open when interacting with it directly.

This script will make your dropdown functional, allowing users to select options like "Salary" or "Business" when they click the "Add Income" button."}],"context":{"currentFile":{"path":"income.html","fsPath":"/Users/Sakshi/PycharmProjects/fintrack/income.html","sources":["opened_tab"],"content":"<!DOCTYPE html>
