Here's how you can modify your HTML and CSS to achieve this:

### CSS Changes

Add styles to make the income and expense lists scrollable:

```css
.tabcontent {
  display: none;
  padding: 6px 12px;
  border-top: none;
  color: white;
  border-radius: 4px;
  height: 400px; /* Set a fixed height for the scrollable area */
  overflow-y: auto; /* Enable vertical scrolling */
}
```

### Explanation

- **Height**: By setting a fixed height (e.g., `400px`) for the `.tabcontent` class, you define the maximum visible area for the content. Adjust this value as needed to fit your design.

- **Overflow**: The `overflow-y: auto;` property ensures that a vertical scrollbar appears when the content exceeds the specified height, allowing users to scroll through the list.

### Updated HTML Structure

Ensure your HTML structure remains the same, as the CSS changes will apply to the existing elements:

```html
<div id="Income" class="tabcontent">
  <h2>Income List</h2>
  <table id="incomeTable">
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>Amount</th>
        <th>Category</th>
        <th>Notes</th>
        <th>Action</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody id="incomeItems">
    </tbody>
  </table>
</div>

<div id="Expense" class="tabcontent">
